JOHANNESBURG ANC struggle veteran Ahmed Kathrada, 87, is in a stable condition in a Johannesburg hospital after undergoing surgery to remove a blood clot on the brain, the Ahmed Kathrada Foundation said on Sunday.Kathrada was operated on on Saturday, foundation director Neeshan Balton said. He had initially been admitted for dehydration but doctors had later picked up the clot.READ: Struggle stalwart Kathrada celebrates 87th birthday Kathrada, despite being ill prior to the operation, was in good spirits. Doctors last night [Saturday] indicated that the operation was successful and he is in a stable condition."However, it will be some time before Kathrada fully recovers, Balton said.Due to hospital regulations and his need to recover only visits from immediate family would be permitted. We do, however, wish to thank the public as well as Kathrada s many friends and comrades for their well-wishes and support. We hope that you continue remembering him in your prayers and take time to reflect on the ideals and values that Kathrada and his generation stood for, Balton said.Kathrada is one of three Rivonia Trialists still alive today, the other two being Andrew Mlangeni and Denis Goldberg.Along with Nelson Mandela, Walter Sisulu, Govan Mbeki, Raymond Mhlaba, and Elias Motsoaledi, they were sentenced in 1964 to life imprisonment on Robben Island during the famous Rivonia Trial.African News Agency